folder: Bank Street & Washington Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Bank Street, south side, from Washington to Greenwich Streets, inclusive. The clearing on the S.W. corner, in the right foreground, is part of the demolition for the railroad viaduct to be built along Washington Street.

The chimney near Greenwich Street belongs to the Hudson Laundry plant at 108 Bank Street and 760 Greenwich Street. No. 110, now an ice plant, occupies the sight (sic) of Governor George Clinton's residence.

July 20, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.

folder: Bank Street & Washington Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
138 Bank Street, at the S.E. corner of Washington Street, showing an abandoned 3 story structure, the demolition of which was requested by the donor of this photo on January 24, 1936. This was accomplished as W.P.A project under the supervision of the Municipal Housing Authority. The lower west side of this building appears here, same constituting Washington Street frontage.

1936

Gift of Committee on Housing
Charity Organisation Society
CREDIT LINE IMPERATIVE
